  "description": "Conversation /message responses currently take 6–15s (PERF-HIGH backlog item). While we have parallelized backend LLM calls, perceived latency is still high because the UI only shows a generic spinner during `loading`. Add a `ReplyProgressIndicator` component (frontend/src/components/conversation/ReplyProgressIndicator.tsx) that displays an animated typing bubble in the chat thread while the assistant reply is in flight. It should: (1) render a three-dot animated bubble styled like an assistant message, (2) cycle through stage labels every ~2.5s — 'Reviewing your message…' (0–2s), 'Crafting reply…' (2–6s), 'Polishing the wording…' (6s+), (3) show an `Xs` elapsed-time counter that ticks each second once the wait exceeds 3s, (4) include `aria-live=\"polite\"` so screen readers announce the wait state, (5) accept an optional `startedAt` prop (number, ms) so the timer is driven by the parent and stays accurate across re-renders.\n\nWiring in `frontend/src/pages/Conversation.tsx`: track `replyStartedAt` (set to `Date.now()` immediately after a user message is appended in `sendMessage`, cleared when the assistant message arrives or on error). Render `<ReplyProgressIndicator startedAt={replyStartedAt} />` at the bottom of the chat scroll area whenever `loading && phase === 'chat'`, replacing the existing generic loading spinner shown there. Auto-scroll the chat to the indicator when it appears so it stays visible on mobile.\n\nAdd a unit test at `frontend/src/__tests__/ReplyProgressIndicator.test.tsx` using @testing-library/react + vitest fake timers covering: initial label, label transitions at 2.5s and 5s, elapsed counter appearing only after 3s, and aria-live attribute presence. This is a pure-frontend change (no backend / schema impact) that materially improves perceived latency without depending on Copilot SDK streaming support.",
